article.description:
Allen Iverson had 23 points as the Philadelphia 76ers snapped a five-game losing streak Monday night
with a 93-71 victory over Denver, sending the Nuggets to their
fifth straight loss.
article.headline: Nuggets score 22 points in first half
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- After a five-game losing streak, the Philadelphia 76ers needed an easy game. They got one against the Denver Nuggets on Monday night. Allen Iverson had 23 points as the 76ers cruised to a 93-71 victory, sending the Nuggets to their fifth straight loss. "Any win is the type of game we needed," said Iverson, who was 9-of-19 from the field. "We had to get that feeling back. It was important for us to get a win before guys started to doubt themselves." Denver scored just 22 points in the first half for the second time this season. The 71 points were the fewest given up by the Sixers this season. Keith Van Horn had 15 points, Todd MacCulloch scored 13 and Brian Skinner 11 for the 76ers, who shot 51 percent to Denver's 39 percent. Rookie Nene Hilario scored a career-high 23 points on 9-for-11 shooting for the Nuggets, who turned the ball over 23 times and dropped to 2-11 on the road. The Nuggets scored four points in an 11:50 stretch bridging the first and second quarters, and Philadelphia used a 25-4 run to take a 34-12 lead. "We wanted to make it tough on them early and then maintain it," said Eric Snow, who left the game with a minor groin strain. The Sixers led 41-22 at the break, the fewest points they have surrendered in a half in team history. "I don't care who you play, they scored 22 points and you have to be excited about that," said Sixers coach Larry Brown, who left the game in the third quarter with an upset stomach. Randy Ayers took over the team in his absence. "I hope this will give us some confidence. sometimes you need that when you are struggling like we are." "There is no excuse for scoring only 22 points," Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "But give some credit to the Sixers defense." Philadelphia's lead reached 26 in the third quarter when Skinner made a layup with 1:30 left. In the fourth, a driving layup by Greg Buckner gave the Sixers their biggest lead, 84-55, with 5:14 remaining. Game notes
Denver's 22 first-half points tied the franchise record. ... Three Denver starters did not score in the first half. ... Philadelphia's Eric Snow left the game in the fourth quarter with a minor groin strain. ... The Nuggets have lost 10 of 11. Their five-game skid matches their longest of the season. ... In his postgame press conference, Iverson wore a vintage Boston Celtics jersey, a No. 6 replica of Hall of Famer Bill Russell. "I just respect the player," he said. "It had to be 33 (Larry Bird), 6 (Russell) or 17 (John Havlicek)."
